{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"170c4847-658b-4490-a3d0-da13b7ff617c","content":"Here's the analysis of **EvalHeavy.csproj** — I found **3 evaluation performance anti-patterns**:\n\n---\n\n### 1. 🔴 File I/O Property Function (line 13)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nReading files during evaluation is expensive — it runs **every time** the project is evaluated (builds, IDE loads, restores). Move this to a target with `Inputs`/`Outputs` so it only runs at execution time when the file changes.\n\n### 2. 🔴 Overly Broad Glob (line 9)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n`**\\*.*` walks the **entire directory tree**. If this repo grows (or contains `.git`, `node_modules`, `packages`, etc.), evaluation slows dramatically. Narrow the glob to specific extensions, or add expensive directories to `$(DefaultItemExcludes)` so all globs skip them.\n\n### 3. 🟡 Chained Import Depth (line 6 → 3 levels)\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nThree nested imports is manageable but forms a pattern that degrades as it grows. Each import adds an evaluation pass. Consider flattening when possible.\n\n---\n\n**Highest-impact fix:** Replace the `File::ReadAllText` call with a build target, and tighten the glob pattern. Those two changes will give the most evaluation speedup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3c9384fc-847d-47b5-92ec-0a8144c22e97","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have a complete picture of the project. Let me analyze it for evaluation performance issues.\n\nIssues I can identify:\n\n1. **File I/O property function**: `$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))` - Reading files during evaluation is expensive. This runs every time the project is evaluated.\n\n2. **Broad glob pattern**: `<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />` - This glob walks the entire directory tree, which is expensive especially if the directory tree is large (e.g., contains node_modules, .git, etc.). The pattern `**\\*.*` is extremely broad.\n   \n3. **Deep import chain**: The props files are nested three levels deep (level1 → level2 → level3), which adds evaluation overhead and could become problematic as the chain grows.\n\n4. **Inefficient exclusion strategy**: The glob uses per-item excludes rather than leveraging `DefaultItemExcludes`, which would be more efficient for filtering out expensive directories.\n\nLet me provide a clear analysis.","outputTokens":680,"requestId":"0402:185A87:480292:5391BE:69F00FFF"},"id":"30ec2507-8849-489c-9a2b-97170ea5722c","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:40:30.737Z","parentId":"4801060c-9fcf-4222-a64e-d384ab4db85d"}
